          "correctOptionId": "opt-1",
          "explanation": "Ans. is \"a' i.e., Km \"The of an enzyme is the concentration of the substrate that enables the enzyme to function at half maximum activity and is therefore a measure of the specificity of a substrate for the enzyme\"___________Clinical biochemistryo Actually enzyme specificity is not measured by Km alone.o It is measured by the ratio Kcat/Km which is a second order rate constant for the reaction between substrate and free enzyme.o This ratio is important, for it provides a direct measure of enzyme efficiency and specificity,o Note : Kcat is turnover number and measures the rate of the catalytic process.",
          "hint": "Topic: Enzyme Kinetics"
