          "correctOptionId": "opt-2",
          "explanation": "The man is experiencing gout attacks, cause by a buildup of uric acid. Uric acid is the end product of purine degradation. The liver contains larger levels of nucleic acids (DNA and RNA) than do the other foods listed as answers, and the intestinal epithelial cells will convert the purines in the food to uric acid and release it into the circulation. The alcohol the man has consumed leads to dehydration, which raises the uric acid concentration to the point where it will precipitate in the blood, leading to the painful episodes.",
